#: main_12.cpp:7216
msgid "About the Rodent chess engines"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7228
msgid "Rodent, written by Pawel Koziol, is a very interesting chess engine."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7230
msgid "It has the UCI_LimitStrength option and also a set of personalities,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7232
msgid "which are loaded from files, for weaker and more varied play."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7235
msgid "For the engine to work properly with the personalities and their"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7237
msgid "opening books, all of the components have to be placed in the same directory."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7239
msgid "They should have been installed in -"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7244
msgid "If you want the Rodent engine to use its own book during a game,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7246
msgid "then you have to switch off the Nimzo_3d opening book from"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7248
msgid "< Main menu > < Openings > < Opening book >"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7250
msgid "or checking the < Book off > option, if you are using the"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7252
msgid "rated game dialog box."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7257
msgid "there is some documentation and a utility program"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7259
msgid "which can be used to make more personalities."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7262
msgid "The Rodent 4 engine package and older versions can be downloaded from -"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7267
msgid "Rodent 4 only, with a detailed review"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7272
msgid "The Rodent 4 engine support material, without engines"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7277
msgid "Rodent 3 support material, without engines"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7296
msgid "A Rodent personality file is simply a list of UCI commands in a *.txt file"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7298
msgid "It is supposed to work in the following manner -"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7300
msgid "The chess program GUI sends the < Personality > command to the Rodent engine."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7302
msgid "The engine then reads the commands from the personality file"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7304
msgid "and adjusts its settings accordingly."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7307
msgid "However, with both Nimzo_3d and the Tarrasch GUI,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7309
msgid "I could not get the engines to work when used in this way."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7311
msgid "All of the personalities played the same moves."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7314
msgid "So instead of this, I intercepted the < Personality > command when it was"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7316
msgid "about to be sent from the GUI to the engine , opened the personality file"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7318
msgid "and sent the commands from the file individually.  This seems to work."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7323
msgid "Essentially, the Rodent engine has two main methods of varying its playing strength."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7325
msgid "It can use ELO limit strength or Nodes per seconds with evaluation blur."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7327
msgid "ELO limit strength allows you to set an approximate ELO rating"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7329
msgid "and nodes per second with evaluation blur lets you set values"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7331
msgid "that have a similar weakening effect."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7334
msgid "The Rodent 3 personalities are set up to use nodes per second "
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7336
msgid "with evaluation blur and Rodent 4 is intended to be used"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7338
msgid "with ELO limit strength only."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7341
msgid "Because of my modification to the way the < Personality > command is sent,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7343
msgid "Rodent 3 can use its personalities with ELO limit strength"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7345
msgid "in combination with evaluation blur and select skill,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7347
msgid "but not with nodes per second."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7352
msgid "It also means that Rodent 4 can use ELO limit strength"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7354
msgid "with evaluation blur and select skill."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7357
msgid "Changing the evaluation blur value slightly means the engine will play"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7359
msgid "different moves without greatly affecting the playing strength,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7361
msgid "so long as the blur value is not too high."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7362
msgid "You can experiment with this, I found that values between 20 - 50"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7364
msgid "worked quite well."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7369
msgid "As well as that, both engines can now use the personality files"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7371
msgid "of the other engine with only minor adjustments from within Nimzo_3d,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7373
msgid "once they have been copied into the < Personalities > directory of the engine."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7375
msgid "This allows you to easily swap in new personality files if you want a change."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7377
msgid "I have placed some in < extra_personalities >"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7379
msgid "within the < Personalities > directory."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7382
msgid "The personality files are stored in the following directories -"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7385
msgid "plus"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7385
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7389
msgid "The files can be modified from within Nimzo_3d to adjust the"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7391
msgid "nodes per second and evaluation blur values and then saved back to disk. "
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7394
msgid "It does not matter that the personality files can end up with commands"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7396
msgid "that are unsuitable for the engine currently in use, because they are"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7398
msgid "filtered out by the GUI before they are sent to the engine."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7403
msgid "Rodent commands"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7420
msgid "These descriptions of the Rodent chess engine personalities are taken from"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7422
msgid "the file < FinalRodent.pdf > which can be found in the following directory -"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7427
msgid "Predefined personalities"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7430
msgid "Since its inception, Rodent project has been about creating an engine"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7432
msgid "that allows modification of its playing style - just like the ChessMaster series,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7434
msgid "only better.  Code changes in the new version meant that old personalities"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7436
msgid "are no longer usable, so I felt the need for creating a new set."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7438
msgid "I hope you will find it interesting."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7441
msgid "Fist and foremost, an attacker, her second consideration"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7443
msgid "is piece activity.  Plays gambit openings."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7446
msgid "Cloe likes closed positions, pawn storms and sound pawn structure."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7448
msgid "The only thing she prefers to a closed position is a closed position"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7450
msgid "with a single open file, owned by her rooks."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7452
msgid "She is a proud practitioner of the French and King's Indian defenses."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7455
msgid "Picture her as a dark - haired, slender, melancholy woman."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7457
msgid "She is a defensive player who likes bishops."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7460
msgid "Imagine him in an expensive suit, looking more like a CEO"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7462
msgid "than a chess player.  Strong, rational, if mildly pessimistic personality."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7464
msgid "Plays solid openings.  Ready to take draw in dead equal positions."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7467
msgid "Imagine him as a player already past his prime,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7469
msgid "disrespectful towards  his opponents and still quite dangerous. "
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7471
msgid "Grumpy likes restricting enemy movement and attacking,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7473
msgid "enjoys closed positions and expects to win."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7475
msgid "Because of his age, he plays mostly not too modern openings."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7477
msgid "For example, he likes the Tarrasch defense."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7480
msgid "Impersonation of Paul Morphy. Emphasizes mobility,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7482
msgid "then king attack, prefers open positions."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7485
msgid "He starts slowly, using openings that do not occupy much space"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7487
msgid "in the center, but don't be lulled in a false sense of security."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7489
msgid "Later he goes for a vicious attacks."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7492
msgid "Picture him as a young, up and coming grandmaster,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7494
msgid "who has not yet reached his true potential."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7496
msgid "Thin, energetic, likes flashy moves a bit too much."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7498
msgid "He tends to part with his pawns from time to time."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7500
msgid "Balanced personality, likely to sacrifice modest amount of material,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7502
msgid "often goes for active defence in the endgame."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7505
msgid "Pedrita stands for pawns, defense, restraint."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7507
msgid "She plays solid openings and thinks defense first, but dont be deceived!"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7509
msgid "She can attack all right if position demands it, and with solid pawn play"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7511
msgid "she is a hard nut to crack."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7514
msgid "Mildly materialistic, but fighting for the initiative"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7516
msgid "and close enough to default to avoid unsound plans."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7518
msgid "Likes to create pressure against enemy pieces."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7520
msgid "Plays closed openings as white, Slav and Caro - Kann defenses as black."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7522
msgid "Perhaps the best setup against the weaker engines."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7525
msgid "Plays without more advanced facets of evaluation function,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7527
msgid "applying sensible default. Slight preference for exchanging queens,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7529
msgid "in dead equal positions will go for a draw."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7531
msgid "Perhaps the most computer - like personality."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7534
msgid "Picture him as a tall man in a brown leather jacket."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7536
msgid "He likes active play but detests being under attack."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7538
msgid "Likes keeping queens on the board."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7541
msgid "Based on Rodent III personality by Brendan J.Norman."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7543
msgid "Plays boa constrictor style, but has strong preference for attack,"
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7545
msgid "likely to sacrifice for positional reasons."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7547
msgid "Much more temperamental version ofGrumpy, very human-like play."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7549
msgid "May be overoptimistic in endgames with queens."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7552
msgid "There are also personalites for many world champions and other famous players."
msgstr ""

#: main_12.cpp:7556
msgid "Rodent 4 chess engine personality descriptions"
msgstr ""
